programSettings.description: Landoltia punctata  cDNAs were reversed transcribed from polyA-selected mRNAs.  SfiIA and SfiIB linkers were added to the cDNAs via the primers used to synthesize first and second strand cDNAs.  The cDNAs were cut with SfiI to generate SfiI sticky ends, and the cDNAs were directionally ligated into SfiIA and SfiIB-cut plasmid vector pTriplEX2.  Recombinant plasmids were transformed into E. coli strain DH5a.
programSettings.welcomeText:
Welcome to the Waksman Institute Summer Experience (WISE)
The research project for the WISE focuses on the genomic analysis of the duckweed Landoltia punctata, and how the genes in this organism compare to other species.
programSettings.overview:
Overview:
The research project for WISE focuses on the genomic analysis of the duckweed Landoltia punctata, and how the genes in this organism compare to other species.

Students in the project will purify plasmid DNA from from bacteria transformed with a Landoltia punctata cDNA library.  They will analyze the duckweed genes using modern molecular biology laboratory techniques, such as restriction enzyme digests, PCR, and agarose gel electrophoresis. The sequences of these cDNAs will be determined and then analyzed by the students using the same bioinformatic tools used by scientists. Students will compare these sequences with genes from other organisms to determine the conservation of specific genes and their evolutionary relationships. Since the sequences of these genes have never been determined before the information the students determine from their analyses will be deposited in databases at the National Center for Biotechnology Information (NCBI) for scientists throughout the world to use. Lists of DNA sequences that were previously published by students in the program can be found at the WSSP web site:  https://wssp.rutgers.edu

In the course of these studies, students and research scientists work together, using the basic principles of molecular biology and genetic engineering to try to solve this research problem. By actually doing science, teachers and students gain an understanding of how science operates.

analysisQuestions.text:
Was there a similar protein in humans? If so, indicate the:
i) Accession number of the human protein
ii) The Protein name.
iii) What does this tell you about the evolution of this protein?
What is the FULL name of your protein? What is the function of your protein? List the sites where you found this information (Books, Google, Wiki, Pubmed etc.)

Search the PDB (https://www.rcsb.org/) with your protein sequence to determine if there is a homologous protein in which the structure has been determined. If there is a match with more than 30% sequence similarity (Positives) indicate:
1. The PDB accession number (4 digit #)
2. Which organism is it from
3. How many -helices and -strands are in the protein.
4. If the -strands are parallel, anti-parallel or mixed.

Perform a BLASTn search of the Transcriptome Shotgun Assembly (TSA) database that is limited to Landoltia punctata (taxid:50518).

A) Enter the sequence ID (number after "gb") of the best contig match and the % sequence identity between the two sequences and the total number of base pairs of the entire contig sequence (not just the region that matches).
B) Download the TSA contig DNA sequence and perform a BLASTx search with the sequence. Does the contig sequence match a protein?
C) If so, indicate the protein Accession number, the name of the protein and the E-value of the match

A) Perform a BLASTp search of the TAIR database.
B) Use the BLASTp matches to search the Arabidopsis Interactome database and answer the following questions:
ii) How many different proteins interact with your protein?
iii) Name one of the proteins (AT number) that interacts with your protein that is biologically significant. Indicate its function

A) Examine the gene expression of the Arabidopsis homolog of your protein in plants by searching the eFP Dataset. Use the homolog you identified in Q5A above. Inidicate which tissues the gene is most highly expressed in.

B) Examine the cell localization of the Arabidopsis homolog of your protein in plants by searching the Cell eFP Browser. Use the homolog you identified in Q5A above. Indicate which organelles in the cell the protein is most highly localized in.

As a scientist investigating this protein in Landoltia, what experiments would youdo next (see Ch. 16 in the Lecture Nots)? Please be specific about the experiments and predict what results you would expect to see.
